data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — it spawns a thread, waits with `Join(timeout)`, and calls `Thread.Abort()` if it exceeds the limit. Three APIs break in .NET 8:

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggered (never thrown) |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> for cancellation
    /// to respond promptly; otherwise cancellation is deferred until the next checkpoint.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner caller experience.
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Overload that accepts work not aware of cancellation.
    /// Cancellation will only take effect between task scheduling boundaries;
    /// the delegate itself cannot be interrupted mid-execution.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => work(), timeout);
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, which forcibly injected an exception, `CancellationToken` only works if the work **checks** it. The backward-compatible `Func<T>` overload preserves your original API but **cannot stop long-running uncooperative code**. Prefer the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload and check the token:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**2. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.**
`CTS` with a timeout creates an internal timer. The `using` statement ensures it's cleaned up. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks.

**3. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.**
The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter distinguishes *our* timeout from an unrelated external cancellation. Only catch what you caused.

**4. Truly uncooperative code (e.g., native calls, third-party libs).**
If you have work that genuinely cannot check a token, the only safe .NET 8 option is to move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`.

**5. `ThreadAbortException` cleanup logic.**
Your original `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` was swallowing the abort to keep the thread alive. In the new model this is simply gone — cancellation is explicit and the code decides what to do via `token.IsCancellationRequested`.
